OBJECT DISAMBIGUATIONS (the object, not the verb):
- FOLDER/directory/folder = object `dirs` (filesystem container).
  "show/list/see THE CONTENT / what is IN FOLDER X" = {list, dirs}:
  you enumerate the FOLDER (list_dirs gives files+subfolders). The object remains `dirs`
  EVEN when the user says "the content" (the content belongs to the folder, not
  a file). NOT files, NOT read (read=file content), NOT render. Only if
  they explicitly ask "the FILES in the folder" -> {list, files}.
- STORE/ARCHIVE/COLLECTION/INTERNAL DB NAMED (e.g. "in store X",
  "in the archive", "collection", "internal database", "local db", "from the
  local db") = object entries: the records of an internal store/db are `entries`
  REGARDLESS of their type ("the issues/expenses saved IN the local db / in the
  store" = {find, entries}, not the live domain object {find, issues}). APPLIES
  ONLY with EXPLICIT store/db/archive context: WITHOUT that word the object
  remains the DOMAIN object (calendar/appointments→events, mail→messages,
  photos→images, files→files). "save/write to store" = {write, entries};
  "delete from store" = {delete, entries}. NOT files (not a file on disk).
- "post/publish a COMMENT" (on an issue, a PR, a thread) = {send,
  messages}: a comment IS an outgoing message. NOT {send, issues} (you do not
  "send" an issue) and NOT write (write = local persistence, not sending).
- "ask/request my approval / confirmation of approval / go-ahead / Approve or Disapprove BEFORE acting" = {get, approval}: human consent gate preceding an action (Approve/Disapprove). NOT {get, persons}
  (persons = biometric registry/faces) and NOT {get, inputs} (inputs = free values from forms).
- INDEPENDENCE between clauses: in a multi-clause query, the object of EACH
  clause is deduced ONLY from its text, NEVER by contamination from nearby
  clauses. Clauses with different objects remain distinct — e.g. "log files" and
  "photos from yesterday" are two different objects (files and images), do not merge them into one because they appear in the same sentence.

