MAPPING: enrollment / biometric registration / face registry = domain "persons" (NOT entries/signatures); enrolling = set, deleting enrollment = delete. Also the IMPLICIT form, without the word "enroll", when presenting a FACE/PERSON to register = enrollment = set/persons: «this is a guest's face», «here are the invited member's photos, register them», «this is a guest» (with photo) → {set, persons}, NOT {classify, images} (you are not labeling photos, you are registering a person).
SEMANTIC PRINCIPLE (universal, apply to ALL objects, not just events):
- Verb CREATE/SET/WRITE/DELETE an entity (destructive/mutating action)
  → map to operational verb (create/set/write/delete/move/send/share).
  Examples: «schedule appointment» = create events, «send email» = send messages,
  «delete file» = delete files, «create folder» = create dirs, «share sheet with Y» = share files (ADR 0128 outbound consent).
- Verb ASK/PROPOSE/SUGGEST/SHOW (inquiry action, read-only) → read.
  Textual synthesis of the result occurs in the planner's final_answer;
  there is NO dedicated describe_<object> executor for most
  objects (exception: describe_numbers for pure numeric lists
  compute statistics). Examples: «propose 3 times» = read events, «show me
  X's files» = read files, «which N are free?» = read events.
- If the sentence mixes both senses («if there is space book the appointment»)
  the winning intent is the MUTATING VERB (create for events post ADR 0128) —
  the check_availability is handled at the planner level as a pre-action
  (read_events).
NOTE ON events vs proposals:
- events = APPOINTMENTS / MEETINGS / CALENDAR ENGAGEMENTS (agenda).
  "schedule/book/schedule/create appointment|meeting|gathering|meeting" = create events (ADR 0128).
- proposals = INTERNAL PROPOSALS of Metnos' synth/introvertive system
  (suggestions to improve the catalog itself). Never user-facing intent.
  If the query talks about "appointment/meeting/gathering/meeting" it is NOT proposals.
SINGLE vs CONTAINER RULE:
When the query distinguishes between SINGLE element and CONTAINER (folder,
group, set), the object is the container if the action treats the container
as a unit (sum/count/sort PER container, work ON THE
container), otherwise it is the element.
- Action on the element (reading, criterion, hash, rendering content,
  modifying the single item): object = element (files, messages, lines, ...).
- Action on the container (popularity, aggregated size, tree structure,
  top containers, creation/deletion of the container itself):
  object = container (dirs, ...).
"find .py" → files (criterion on singles).
"find largest directories" → dirs (on containers).
"count totals aggregating by folder" → dirs (aggregate on container).
"count files in a folder" → find/files (you count ELEMENTS: object=files, verb=find because you enumerate to count; NOT get, NOT dirs).
"how many files are in album X" → find/files.
"total size of path" → dirs (on container).
"subdirectory structure" → dirs (on container).
"create folder" → dirs (action on the container itself).

COMPOUND (MORE ACTIONS IN SEQUENCE):
If the request contains MORE actions in sequence (typical: "do X and then Y",
"find ... and write ...", "take ... and put them ...", "download ... and send ..."),
respond with a JSON ARRAY of {verb,object} objects, ONE per action, IN THE ORDER
of execution. Each clause carries ITS real object (the object on which THAT
action acts), NEVER a single global object repeated. Single action → a single
JSON object, not an array.
METHOD (apply ALWAYS on long queries): FIRST segment the sentence at connectors
(comma, "and", "then", "so") and COUNT verbs/imperatives; THEN emit EXACTLY
one JSON object for each segment, no fewer. Each imperative is an action:
"send me/share with me" = send/share (NOT render); "attach/add photo X"
= an action on images (find/get); "save to store" and "create sheet" are TWO
distinct actions. Do not merge two imperatives into one, do not discard the last one.
